Approach & Complexity

We can model this problem using a Disjoint Set Union (DSU) to keep track of the connected components.
The core mathematical observation is how the "beauty" changes when two components merge.
Initially, a single node `x` has a beauty of 1 (the range [x, x]).
When we merge Set A and Set B, the new beauty isn't just `beauty(A) + beauty(B)`. If an element `x` from Set A connects with `x-1` or `x+1` in Set B, two separate ranges fuse into a single continuous range, reducing the total beauty by 1 for each adjacent connection.

To merge efficiently, we use a technique called "Small-to-Large Merging". 
We maintain the actual elements of each component in a hash set. When merging, we always iterate through the elements of the smaller set and insert them into the larger set. 
For every element `x` moving from the smaller set to the larger set:
1. If `x - 1` is already in the larger set, decrement the combined beauty by 1.
2. If `x + 1` is already in the larger set, decrement the combined beauty by 1.
3. Add `x` to the larger set.

Time Complexity: O(Q + N log N). Searching and adding to a Python set is O(1) on average. Due to Small-to-Large merging, each element is moved at most log(N) times.
Space Complexity: O(N) to store the parent array, component sets, and beauty values.


Python 3 Solution

import sys

def solve():
    sys.setrecursionlimit(200000)
    input_data = sys.stdin.read().split()
    if not input_data:
        return
        
    n = int(input_data[0])
    q = int(input_data[1])
    t = int(input_data[2])
    
    parent = list(range(n + 1))
    elements = [{i} for i in range(n + 1)]
    beauty = [1] * (n + 1)
    
    def find(i):
        if parent[i] == i:
            return i
        parent[i] = find(parent[i])
        return parent[i]
        
    def union(i, j):
        root_i = find(i)
        root_j = find(j)
        if root_i != root_j:
            # Small-to-Large Merging
            if len(elements[root_i]) > len(elements[root_j]):
                root_i, root_j = root_j, root_i
                
            beauty[root_j] += beauty[root_i]
            
            for x in elements[root_i]:
                if (x - 1) in elements[root_j]:
                    beauty[root_j] -= 1
                if (x + 1) in elements[root_j]:
                    beauty[root_j] -= 1
                elements[root_j].add(x)
                
            parent[root_i] = root_j
            elements[root_i] = None # Free up memory
            
    idx = 3
    total_ans = 0
    
    for _ in range(q):
        type_q = int(input_data[idx])
        u = int(input_data[idx+1])
        v = int(input_data[idx+2])
        idx += 3
        
        if type_q == 1:
            union(u, v)
        else:
            root_u = find(u)
            total_ans += beauty[root_u]
            
    print(total_ans)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    solve()


